Author: notwoodenshoes
Content: final thoughts ||Ryuki route is super interesting and the best part of the game. Tama and Ryuki work really well together and seeing the mental deterioration occur was very intense but very intriguing at the same time. The mizuki route started off promising but once the timeline twist happened the game completely flew off the rails in the worst way possible. So much of it feels like repeats of stuff Uchikoshi has already done, from the intentional hiding of the date to trick you to the magical suicide virus to the secret clones, the ending just being a ripoff of AI1's ending, it's very disappointing. It's also very strange that the twist from the first game didn't come back around besides to make a joke about Date's appearance. The Somniums were much better this time (with the exception of the Masked Girl's and Tokiko's), with Shoma's being my favorite. Way too many dance sequences, and the QTEs just feel so weird, like they didn't really fit in. The Date fakeout as well seemed really dumb. Tearer wasn't a very good villain either, like he needed something more to him for things to really click together. Ultimately it's an Uchikoshi game through and through||

Author: nak44
Content:
no explicit spoilers but responding to potentially spoilery post-game sentiment so just in case:

||reading through all the outraged reax im reminded of a guy in <#974341120198844467> the other day who was like "i logically get all the issues Joe has with the twists, i just can't bring myself to care"

it feels like there's a huge gulf between people who see the contrived shit uchi does to make his twists work and go "haha, classic uchikoshi, cool twist btw" and people who go "this is UNACCEPTABLE WRITING and i HATE EVERY MOMENT OF MY EXISTENCE PLAYING THIS"

personally, i'm in the former camp. i really don't see anything inherently wrong with starting with an idea for a twist and then building the story around that. it usually makes character writing much harder since "slice of life"/character development scenes and dialogue that would be innocuous in other stories can drastically compromise the structure of an intricately-plotted uchikoshi-style story, and uchikoshi doesn't _really_ ever overcome that challenge to make truly emotionally impactful stories. But cmon, I'm here for the twist buildup and the twist reveal, I can live with characters acting like plot devices in service of that. ||

Author: nak44
Content:
continuing, now with explicit spoilers for both games:

||that all said, i do prefer AI 1 slightly more since it managed to hit those emotional character highs at points,  particularly in Mayumi's route. And I think that's no coincidence - the twist in AI 1 imposed much fewer restrictions on the way the story can be structured, only really directly restricting the behavior of people who got body-swapped; everyone else was relatively free to act like an actual human being. Whereas in AI 2, essentially everybody must behave in service of the timeline twist, awkwardly tiptoeing around details that would give away the twist right up until it's about to be revealed. I think Ryuki got shafted the hardest, with his mental illness struggles mostly existing to sow confusion over the realiability of his narrative.

So I absolutely agree something is lost when a twist becomes so ambitious it puts chains on the rest of the writing, I just think it's a tradeoff that can be worth it. I'm inherently sympathetic to these authors like uchikoshi and the sekimeiya guys who want to pull off something mind-blowing and grand while still delivering at least some of the beats of a normal story. Writing an engaging story without any particular restrictions is hard enough; even pulling half of one off with the goals these ontological-adjacent mystery writers set for themselves is impressive to me.||

Author: nak44
Content: ||it's especially confusing to me for people to be several games deep into uchi's catalogue and still getting super mad over stuff like the double cathedral or a misleading narrative presentation. like, what are you guys even here for?||

Author: maulwurfpinguin
Content:
ZE ||to be fair, I haven't actually finished the game, I've just had a gander at the spoilers, so I might not be getting the whole picture here, but I don't think the problem with this game is that the twist is out there. I think the problem is that the game actively lies to you, to get the twist to work. VLR doesn't lie to you ~~about the timeline lul~~, 999 doesn't lie to you, they present their info right in front of your eyes and you can figure the main twists for both those games, and people are rightfully annoyed at the parts that were explicitly obscured in the games.
Meanwhile, this game tells you "here is a timeline, uwu" and then explicitly goes "actually ahahaha that isn't the timeline lol SUCKAAAA" and that really sucks for a murder mystery story. Like, a big aspect of the murder mystery genre is that you should be able to figure out who the killer is or how the murders happened *before* the game reveals it to you, and when it purposely obscures information from the player in order to create a surprising twist, this is simply impossible.||

Author: maulwurfpinguin
Content: ||This was also possible in game 1 - the game drops hints for date and the old cyclops killings being related, it hints at mindmelding using psyncing etc - sure the game doesn't tell you till you are further in that you can outright swap minds with the psync machine, but it's 100% a thing you can predict based on the evidence presented to you. And then you have the fact that many people liked that the first game was more grounded, aside from the sci-fi elements that were explicitly established in game. Like, I liked that Naix was a bamboozle, I liked that Uchi seemed to be trying to write a different kind of story... until it fell down during the epilogue when they implied morbing was real lol||

Author: nak44
Content:
||first off, i fully admit to being someone who just wants to passively consume a mystery rather than taking on the challenge of solving it, so I straight-up don't care if the mystery is "unfair" or "lies to you". But even given that, when I was playing AI 2 and discussing it with friends in DMs, we all picked up on timeline weirdness relatively early on into Mizuki route, so I'm not buying that the twist is impossible this time. Hell, you have A Flurry Of Owls up there dropping a ton of consecutive instances of the "timeline discrepencies" showing up more and more as you get closer to the twist reveal - if he stopped right there and thought hard about what could explain the supposed time gap between most of the body halves, is it really "impossible" to figure out? The first major clue is Shoma's disappearance from the Ferris wheel back in Ryuki's route; once you start suspecting timeline shenanigans, it seems very natural for that event + Ryuki's established memory issues to link in and provide the foundation for a solved mystery.

Is it fair? Not really, there is no principled way to single out the flowchart presentation alone as truly misleading and every other relevant clue as reliable. But with how many people I've seen notice relevant clues once they get past about 1/3rd into Mizuki route, I'm hard-pressed to see how it's impossible for someone to stumble onto the answer.||

Author: maulwurfpinguin
Content:
||As I said, I didn't actually finish the game yet, that was just the impression I got from reading the spoilered bits here in chat lol. Sure, it could be possible to pick up on timeline weirdness all by yourself, but still, it's against mystery best practices to actively lie to your audience. Usually, you want to present something to your audience, so the answer is right in their face, but they don't get it until you give them that 1 final clue - here, the game just outright lies to you as far as I know, which annoys people. This is also why people (DRV3 case 1) haaaaaaaate the Kaede twist, since the game actively hides Kaede's thoughts from you. The person I played V3 with still managed to guess it, but they weren't happy that the only way to make a twist work was to present it dishonestly.||
||Then there's stuff like there being clones but cloning apparently not even being the solution to the mystery? TWo cathedrals? Another hidden love child from So? The whole simulation theory nonsense? It all just seems increadibly stupid to me, and I remember thinking prior to the game releasing, that I wouldn't want these to be involved. But again, I've read these out of context and haven't finished the game yet||

Author: nak44
Content:
||Putting aside the substance of the game, I strongly encourage you to finish rather than be swayed by internet negativity. In my personal experience whenever I read people complaining about a piece of media it always brings me down and demotivates me from starting or finishing the work - but once I do, the complaints are almost always overblown and I think my time was well spent, even if it a lot of the complaints were ultimately valid. If nothing else, I think it's a shame to let other people form your opinion for you, and I can attest that at least some of what you're worried about isn't a big deal (at least in my opinion).

As for fair play mysteries and all that, like I said earlier I don't go into these stories expecting to be able to solve them, so the Kaede twist didn't bother me either. That's legitimately just different strokes though, so no getting past it.||

Author: thefuryofowls
Content:
alright, went a bit further and I mostly have had my questions/concerns explained by the game, though there is still a pretty fucking huge one, that I doubt is going to be addressed: ||So, you're telling me that Bibi ***went to crime scenes and shit years ago dressed like Present-Mizuki?*** and no one, not a single one of the characters aside from Date that one time, noticed how she looked just fucking like 12-year-old-Mizuki (i realize that Lien & Kizuna would know the character independent from Mizuki, but it's still some bullshit that they call her "mizuki" sometimes, despite never using that name for her otherwise) ***MUCH LESS*** how Bibi ***STILL SHOWS UP AS "MASKED WOMAN" TO RYUKI AT LEAST ONCE*** which implies, no, she's actually maybe-dressed like "Masked Woman" the whole time (so why would police let her onto crime scenes, etc), to speak nothing of the fact that we're simply not-privvy to Bibi's involvement despite ***RYUKI SUPPOSEDLY FUCKING KNOWING ABOUT IT***||

Content: probably good. its a real monkeys paw when you enjoy some previous material of any sort of media. Once its over your left with a deep longing for more. Like you just wanted that previous good thing to stay consistently good forever. Its stupid to feel that way but its the way I'm programmed. So I'm happy the sequel exists, it's wearing the first game like a mask, it makes the same motions, it does something original and interesting. But it's not the same game, it didn't move me in the exact same ways. That's the source of my confliction.

Author: thefuryofowls
Content:
alright, i've finished the game, gotten all the endings as far as I can tell and i think i've settled on my thoughts about the game:

In short, it's pretty good, but I didn't personally enjoy it as much as the first game, and while the first one is an easy recommendation to anyone I know generally, I wouldn't say this one is for lots of reasons.

spoilery thoughts/discussion (full game for AI-1 & AI-2, you've been warned):
||I simply think there are too many combinations of dumb-shit, coincidences, and what i'll call "writing black holes" to be satisfying, *especially* as a "murder mystery". In the first game, aside from the huge twist of "body swapping is a thing" and the coincidence of "on one path, Saito gets in a car crash", everything logically follows, makes sense, and you can even reason about it, and there are essentially no loose ends by the epilogue. Even the implied morbing is also explained by the "fractal amnesia" thing, which is true to real life even. In AI-2, there are just too many things that have to be deliberately hidden from the player through "don't-think-about-it" black holes, writing contrivances, and actual proper unreliable narrator type shenanigans. This is all ignoring some of the other glaring issues like how some Somniums are fucking awful to play through (Tokiko & "Masked Woman"/Bibi are primary offenders)||

Now do all these things make the game bad? No, I still think it's pretty good, just not something I'll look back at as fondly as the first game

I realize people didn't exactly ask, but I thought I'd share in case people wanted to chat with me about it or similar

Author: nak44
Content: This is pretty much the consensus opinion on every point except some people list everything you said and conclude "pretty good" and some people conclude "godawful, actually the worst thing uchi has ever done"

Author: thefuryofowls
Content: I'm surprised it's "worst thing uchi has ever done" for some people

Author: thefuryofowls
Content: mostly because I don't see how you look at AI-2, and VLR (or any ZE game IMO) in the same breath and not see the same genes/etc

Author: nak44
Content: The vibe I get is that the first game's more restrained mystery allowed for better character writing that got people invested, and then AI2's craziness made everyone feel more like plot devices and betrayed that investment

Author: nak44
Content: The fact that it's pretty typical uchikoshi with probably more rough edges also means people think the twist isn't novel enough to impress them and justify the contrivances

Author: nak44
Content: Personally, I quite liked the moment to moment experience of "man, something's just not right here" to ||"wait, are they fucking with the timeline or presentation"|| to ||"oh my god uchi you glorious bastard" (at the timeline twist)||

Author: thefuryofowls
Content:
Yeah, mostly the thing about the twist is that I just don't see what the purpose of it is narratively

the best I could argue is that it essentially ||is a "double-twist" of, timeline was wrong, also 2 mizuki's|| which... is just sorta... whatever narratively I guess?
it ends up creating more issues than it introduces as intrigue, so I see what is meant by "isn't novel enough to impress them and justify the contrivances". 

That being said, most of the rest is fine, it's just annoying that ||almost like, 80% of the narrative post-twist is *all* to explain how shit didn't "leak out" to Mizuki finding out about stuff that Ryuki/Bib knew, because 6 years is a long time for *no fucking progress or updates to happen*, along with lots of other issues|| so again, the twist (||timeline stuff, two mizukis is actually fine IMO or could be||) could almost not exist and it wouldn't really change much to be honest

Author: nak44
Content: I think most uchi games have moments of that sort of uneasiness, whereas this one did a pretty good job of sustaining it throughout

Author: truth12885
Content: I'm gonna dismantle every point here now real quick. ||Mizuki not being "with her birth parents" in the first game... doesn't matter? Of course the two Mizukis would have the same modifications in the same lab - the lab made them. Of course they went to the same orphanage, it was being run by the research facility's benefactor. The same bike with the same jet engine, same clothes, and similar attitudes can be chalked up to Boss - she raised Bibi long before the HB killings six years prior, and the files for the Present says she adopted Mizuki, which sure, is probably a hint for Bibi's existence, but at the same time _someone_ had to look after Mizuki for those six years Date went missing. Why wouldn't she give her the same uniform and the same gear Bibi had? As for why they never interacted six years ago, I mean, Bibi knew where Mizuki was at, so she was clearly avoiding running into her. She put on the mask when she either a) was somewhere that Mizuki could pop up easily  (like Lemniscate) or b) where Mizuki already was going to be (like the docks when rescuing Shoma).||

Content: The list would be very long but the worst ones that spring to mind are: ||1) Komeji picking up half a corpse (I know he was drunk but holy fucking shit wtf who does that) to blackmail a serial killer he doesn't even know the identity of. 2) Bibi finds a suspicious room under the research lab with clear ties to the killer, leaves and never mentions it again (it is found 6 years later again by Mizuki who just randomly learnt about it on her off day). 3) Bibi randomly decides that on the even days of the first investigation she's going to dress like a ninja for no discernible reason. 4) Ryuki decides to not investigate a crime scene for 6 years even though critical information was there. 5) Multiple times when you wink psynk a person of interest they mention suspicious shit (Mostly Lien) and you dont investigate it further until it's literally spelled out to the protagonist that this is related to the case. 6) for some reason the police didn't know that Amame was Komeji's daughter, something that wasn't kept a secret||

Author: truth12885
Content: So, first, ||I don't remember what happened the Ryuki day after Bibi and Lien found the secret basement, so I can't really comment on why that happened.|| the rest, though, can be explained pretty easily: ||3) she's a ninja specifically when she's in locations that Mizuki could easily come to (like Lemniscate) or she knows Mizuki will definitely be (the harbor while rescuing Shoma). It isn't "for no reason", she literally calls herself a ninja because she's meant to be a secret to a lot of people. 4) I'm not sure what crime scene you're talking about, but any three of them aren't a problem; we don't know Ryuki didn't investigate the classroom where Chikara's right half was (it's not like there were any clues there to begin with), he most likely DID investigate Dvaita where Komeji was killed, or else he didn't because Tearer got to him first and took control over Ryuki (since that's the day you play as Bibi, where Ryuki shoots her and you learn about his betrayal, so it happened very recently, and not on the day prior, where you _were_ Ryuki), and the Cathedral... well, there's a lot of baggage there for him, so it's obvious why he'd avoid it. 5) people being suspect in a Wink Psync doesn't automatically mean it's connected to the case. You can't really investigate a lead you don't know is a lead, right? Especially ABIS, since they need to be certain they can glean important information during Psyncs. 6) I know the 'you didn't ask' plotpoint can be lame, but there's no reason for anyone to question Amame's parentage enough to look into it. She isn't even a person of interest.||

Author: truth12885
Content: this is gonna get CIA'd for a hot minute <:Jomseph:959729899634061322>

Author: enyo9895
Content: ||3) but WHY is she a secret, i cant think a reason for her to be. The only in universe reason I can think of is to prevent Mizuki from knowing? which seems like a shitty reason. Also how did she know that she wouldn't run into Mizuki on the even days? If she wants to prevent her from finding out the only logical thing to do is to walk around in your ninja suit all the time. It would creep people out but she doesn't seem to care on the even days when she is wearing it so why not? 4) I'm talking about Komeji's crime scene - he doesn't look into it until 6 years later and it's what leads him to Amame. If he did what he did at the other crime scenes then he would have found tearer there and then. 5) the people you're looking at are persons of interest in a case - if they see suspicious shit you go after them until you know that it's not. 6) again, police not knowing who the son/daughter of a suspect is can only be gross incompetence||

Author: truth12885
Content: 7) ||Gen did know the body was in the freezer, that's why he never unlocked it. As for why he didn't get rid of it, maybe he just didn't want to chance it. If the body was hidden elsewhere then he couldn't be sure it'd stay hidden, which ruins the point of him hiding it for Amame's sake. 8) Nobody realizes there are two cathedrals until the end. Ryuki didn't talk about what he saw in the Cathedral 2 likely due to the TC-PERGE infecting him at that point, and he went too crazy to remember, having an episode thinking it was 6 years ago. 9) Gen wouldn't be arrested for what he did, since the statue of limitations was up. At the least, they didn't need to send the Super Police for it. Mizuki's never been good with just accepting authority doing what it wants, y'know? 10) Boss probably gave special permission for Date and the Mizukis to go into the Stadium alone. The reason no one else went is because, well, they need to keep the border around it. And they're dealing with an infectious virus, so the less people in the imminent blast zone, the better.||

Author: truth12885
Content: my guy, I just explained half of this <:tueaday:587355378962923522>

Author: truth12885
Content: ||She's a secret because "hey Mizuki you're a clone, here's the original clone" is a pretty heavy thing to just, let slip. Bibi has been looking after Mizuki from afar, I don't think it's wild that she'd have a good idea where not to go un-disguised. Plus, she was disguised for Ryuki too, who wasn't supposed to know about her either. Him knowing is a mistake due to his betrayal. 4) I just gave reasons as to why Ryuki might have, or might not have, investigated Studio Dvaita - maybe he did, _did_ find Tearer, and that's how Tearer got him under his thumb. Or he didn't, because Tearer called him to the Cathedral first, so he was blackmailed into not investigating. Either way, the day immediately after Komeji's death is when Ryuki got strong-armed into being a pawn for Tearer, and that definitely affected his ability to investigate further. 5) for the most part, they aren't. There are seemingly superficial connections at first, but it isn't until those connections become _clear_ they're related to the case, then they start looking into it. That, like, isn't an issue.||

Author: zephex98
Content: I just reached the first lock on Mizuki route , after ||tearer somnium|| and I think I figured out even more. I am going to spoiler tag my prediction that would explain a lot of details because doubt people might believe i was able to figure it out if dont write it before confirmation, i also havent checked to timeline to confirm it just in case. So; ||I originally thought both POVs were actually somehow happening at the same time, that there were no past/future division, there are too many details that conflic with that but also many that make sense if they do. But I might have figured out. There arent 2 POVs, there are 3. Left side is 100% Ryuki, in the past, whose perspective is only partially revealed somehow (probably perge). Right is Mizuki, but hers intertwine with the "Masked Woman" who is the OG Mizuki, Mizuki Date being a clone of her. That explains the line that fucked me the most "I have a younger sister" just how tf?! And I always noticed that the files mention Boss adopted Mizuki, and Boss talks in game about her in both routes. I think Mizuki Date memory about Older Mizuki are also messed somehow or for some reason. So there are 2 POVs in the past, which explains A LOT OF DETAILS and 1 in the future which EXPLAINS A LOT OF DETAILS. These shenaningans might be part of Nirvana Initiative in purpose by Tearer on Naix, which I hope goes 100% pure meta, like, DDLC style but with a much more interesting and complex context. I think the lamest way this could go if it is just a DR2 situation instead. Regardless of how it will actually end, the fact that this games biggest mysteries arent even about the case itself but meta mysteries and they have messed with my head so much is already a huge plus in my book, i am having a blast||

A1: he is an unemployed uni dropout who is into idolshit

Q2.1: why did he drop out of uni?
A2.1: his excuse is that he wanted to focus on writing, but really he couldnt handle it
Q2.2: why is he unemployed?
A2.2: he doesn't understand how dire his family situation is or chooses to ignore it to avoid responsibility as his mother continues to pamper him
Q2.3: why is he into idolshit?
A2.3: he craves for love in an unhealthy way as his father is dead and his mother has dementia

Q3.1: why couldnt he handle the uni?
A3.1: hes infantile and his mother keeps feeding into that
Q3.2: why is his mother continuing to pamper him?
A3.2: she has dementia and still essentially sees him as a child
Q3.3: why is his family situation dire?
A3.3: theyre deep in debt with the mafia, and the diner had to close due to no traffic as the nearby area was declared off-limits

Author: kusoro
Content: i see the dumb fucking writing advice "dont answer mysteries in a way that generates more questions" a lot

Author: kusoro
Content: its idiotic

Author: kusoro
Content: its not possible

Author: kusoro
Content: ANY answer will give the reader more questions to ask

Author: kusoro
Content: eventually youre going to have to hit the "suspend your disbelief" wall, one way or another

Author: kusoro
Content: and the advice is actually counterproductive as it leads to shallow stories if you go "suspend your disbelief" too early

Author: kusoro
Content: the better way to phrase the intent as i understand it behind this advice is "dont answer mysteries in a way that has questions left unanswered, unless this mystery is in itself an answer to some other mystery"

Author: kusoro
Content: or more simply put "say suspend your disbelief only if its a question residing somewhere around the third level of questioning"

Author: truth12885

Author: tictac5184
Content: ||I haven't gotten far enough for any of the real mysteries of the game to be explained at all, but the things set up do not interest me because I don't find any of the potential explanations the game is hinting at compelling. I find I am intrigued by the mysteries and then another character mentions Simulation Theory, finding seams or tearing and I groan through my skin. I'm very done with "villain" is a fully masked clothed character with a magic voice changer also. In regards to the Komeji ending, while I liked Shoma the whole thing is infuriating because I find Komeji a thoroughly unlikeable character. His motivations of following his dream because he 'wants to make people smile' falls hollow when he makes nobody smile because he is absolutely terrible at his craft, and no-one finds him funny or comes to see him. Guy refuses to just get a steady job when he does one literal paid gig a month for $50, that he could fit into any Sunday, and puts his family in danger by getting involved with literal Yakuza rather than just provide. And then we have to spend the last 10 minutes of that ending with Shoma apologising as if any of his feelings or actions towards his deadbeat father weren't warranted (breaking the gold star is a dick move though).||

Author: truth12885
Content: I see it as a snowball effect. ||It's not that Komeji is enthusiastically getting in with the Yakuza, it's just that things got to that point in the first place. It started as not-a-problem, when he first made the jump to comedian, but then he needed a loan, and then he needed more loans, and then he needed to deal with the first loan, and he's not making money so he gets another loan, and... Not to say this really justifies it or anything, but it isn't supposed to be that clear cut.|| of course, I fully expected him to be a ||shitty selfish performer archetype, so seeing him be just a normal dude trying to be a good dad, that endeared me a lot|| <:Jomseph:959729899634061322>
